text: Just saw that
I appreciate the sentiment, but I think there are much bigger problems than eminence at this point
Eminence, etc should never have been made. They knew this back after Oloro. But let's move on.
I actually like Eminence (in concept) because it's limited to tribes, but yea... Command Zone effects are a mistake.
... what eminence cards are causing issues?
...? Are they problems?
Only deck you'll ever see is vampire. Even then... usually the last worry in the pod
I never get the "they're a problem" comment. Why?
They're not. Not liking a mechanic isn't banworthy
But what even IS the argument? "I don't like them so they're a problem?" Surely, people cannot be that emotional
Like I hate chaos effects. They're the WORST, to me. But I don't think they're a problem

When we measured salty cards, the ones that got the highest scores were the ones that reduced interactivity within a game. Stasis, Armageddon, etc. One of those lands and people can't realistically play or interact with the game anymore

Eminence is definitionally non-interactable. I can kill your atraxa, but I can't stop your Edgar from spitting out tokens. Literally no way to stop that ability, no kill spell will reach into the command zone.

Keep in mind that this isn't my personal take - this is just why people don't like it. I actually like the concept of Eminence, particularly the tribal commanders, since they force a very specific deckbuilding constraint, and that is very interactive. It's like when people in Modern complain about Delver of Secrets - "Why does Blue get a 1 mana 3/2 flyer?" well, they get it because it forces a specific deck constraint to actually work. But anyway, even with that said, I get why people are displeased with the execution, and I don't think it's the type of thing they can or should return to often

I do think that keeping it restricted to tribes (or even archetypes) is the right call. That's why I've never truly gotten the HUGE protest. Edgar isn't "Get a token every time you cast a creature" meaning he's THE Mardu token deck, bar none.

Gavin has spoken about the Eminence design several times, saying that it's meant to require you to play the creatures and you have to have them to gain any benefit, vs. Oloro which just sits there and does it's thing without any outside resources spent.
